The board shall consist of the following voting members:
President, or a designee, of the University of Kentucky, who shall serve as co-chair of the board;
President, or a designee, of the University of Louisville, who shall serve as co-chair of the board;
Commissioner, or a designee, of the Department for Public Health;
Commissioner, or a designee, of the Department for Medicaid Services;
Executive director, or a designee, of the Commonwealth Office of Technology; and
Nine (9) at-large members appointed by the Governor as follows:
One (1) member engaged in the business of large-scale e-strategy and computer information technology;
One (1) member engaged in the business of health insurance who is employed by a company that has its headquarters in Kentucky;
Two (2) members from a list of four (4) individuals recommended by the Kentucky Hospital Association, one (1) representing rural hospitals, and one (1) representing urban hospitals;
Two (2) physicians actively engaged in the practice of medicine in the Commonwealth from a list of four (4) physicians recommended by the Kentucky Medical Association, or self-nominated;
One (1) member from a company with at least one thousand (1,000) employees selected from a list of four (4) individuals submitted by the Associated Industries of Kentucky;
One (1) member with experience as a physician practice manager; and
One (1) member at large.

The board shall consist of the following ex officio members who may vote, but shall not be counted toward a quorum:
Commissioner, or a designee, of the Department of Commercialization and Innovation;
President, or a designee, of the Council on Postsecondary Education;
Secretary, or a designee, of the Cabinet for Health and Family Services;
Commissioner, or a designee, of the Department of Insurance;
Two (2) members of the Senate who are members of the Interim Joint Committee on Health and Welfare or the Interim Joint Committee on Banking and Insurance, appointed by the President of the Senate; and
Two (2) members of the House of Representatives who are members of the Interim Joint Committee on Health and Welfare or the Interim Joint Committee on Banking and Insurance, appointed by the Speaker of the House.

The board may appoint committees or subcommittees with the charge of investigating and making recommendations to the board on specific aspects of the Ke-HN, including but not limited to evidence-based clinical decision support, security of protected information, electronic data interchange, and clinical practice software packages, including the feasibility of developing a software purchasing alliance to decrease the cost of software and tax incentives to encourage members of the network to purchase software deemed by the board to meet the standards of KRS 216.267. The board may appoint the following committees:
Clinical Decision Support Committee;
Privacy and Security of Protected Health Information Committee;
Electronic Data Interchange Committee; and
Clinical Software Review Committee.

The Clinical Decision Support Committee membership shall include at least the following members:
One (1) physician with expertise in health informatics;
Two (2) physicians actively engaged in the practice of medicine in this Commonwealth from a list of four (4) physicians recommended by the Kentucky Medical Association, or self-nominated;
One (1) representative of a rural hospital and one (1) representative of an urban hospital;
One (1) pharmacist;
One (1) representative engaged in the business of health-care information technology;
Two (2) members with experience as physician practice managers, one (1) from a single-physician practice and one (1) from a multiphysician practice; and
One (1) member engaged in the business of health insurance who is recommended by the Kentucky Association of Health Plans, Incorporated.

The Privacy and Security of Protected Health Information Committee shall include at least the following members:
One (1) physician actively engaged in the practice of medicine in this Commonwealth;
Two (2) members with expertise in HIPAA regulations;
Two (2) members engaged in the business of large-scale e-strategy and computer information technology;
One (1) member who serves as a computer information officer within the health-care industry;
Two (2) members with experience as physician practice managers, one (1) from a single-physician practice and one (1) from a multiphysician practice;
One (1) member engaged in the business of health insurance who is recommended by the Kentucky Association of Health Plans, Incorporated; and
One (1) representative of a hospital.

The Electronic Data Interchange Committee shall include at least the following members:
Two (2) members engaged in the business of large-scale e-strategy and computer information technology;
Two (2) members engaged in the business of health insurance who are recommended by the Kentucky Association of Health Plans, Incorporated;
Executive director, or a designee, of the Office of Administrative and Technology Services within the Cabinet for Health and Family Services;
Two (2) members with experience as physician practice managers, one (1) from a single-physician practice and one (1) from a multiphysician practice; and
One (1) representative of a hospital.

The Clinical Software Review Committee shall include at least the following members:
One (1) member from a company that develops computer software for physician practices;
One (1) member engaged in the business of large-scale e-strategy and computer information technology;
Three (3) physicians, with one (1) having experience in electronic information technology;
Two (2) members with experience as physician practice managers, one (1) from a single-physician practice and one (1) from a multiphysician practice;
One (1) member engaged in the business of health insurance who is recommended by the Kentucky Association of Health Plans, Incorporated or employed by a company which has its headquarters in Kentucky; and
One (1) representative of a hospital.
